00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:01.259
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:01.259 --> 00:01:03.050
MICHAEL MAUBOUSSIN:
Thank you, [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:03.820
And good afternoon.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:05.695
It's a real pleasure to
be here, and I really

00:01:05.695 --> 00:01:07.310
look forward to
today's discussion.

00:01:07.310 --> 00:01:10.930
The topic today is an
unendingly fascinating topic

00:01:10.930 --> 00:01:12.350
of skill and luck.

00:01:12.350 --> 00:01:13.970
I'll tell you my
own story of luck.

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:15.470
When I was a senior
in college I had

00:01:15.470 --> 00:01:17.178
no idea what I wanted
to do with my life,

00:01:17.178 --> 00:01:19.014
but I did know I needed a job.

00:01:19.014 --> 00:01:20.430
I went to school
in Washington, DC

00:01:20.430 --> 00:01:21.660
and one of the firms
that came to recruit

00:01:21.660 --> 00:01:23.240
was Drexel Burnham Lambert.

00:01:23.240 --> 00:01:25.290
Now this is probably
before most of your time.

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:27.800
But it was a fairly hot
investment bank at the time.

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:30.220
On campus interview--
did sufficiently well

00:01:30.220 --> 00:01:32.670
that I was invited to
New York for the big day.

00:01:32.670 --> 00:01:35.710
So I get my very best
suit out, polish my shoes,

00:01:35.710 --> 00:01:36.610
go to New York.

00:01:36.610 --> 00:01:38.110
The day of the big
interviews, we're

00:01:38.110 --> 00:01:41.140
sitting around a conference
room and they go,

00:01:41.140 --> 00:01:42.339
here is the basic setup.

00:01:42.339 --> 00:01:44.630
You're going to have six
interviews with various people

00:01:44.630 --> 00:01:46.180
from our training
program, and you're

00:01:46.180 --> 00:01:48.930
going to get 10 minutes
with the head guy.

00:01:48.930 --> 00:01:50.680
So of course, you want
to be good all day.

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:53.774
But for those 10 minutes make
sure you have your A game.

00:01:53.774 --> 00:01:55.190
So I go through
my six interviews.

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:56.950
They go reasonably well.

00:01:56.950 --> 00:01:58.040
I get my 10 minutes.

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:01.400
I'm ushered into this
guy's huge office,

00:02:01.400 --> 00:02:04.680
and I see peeking out
from underneath his desk

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:07.210
a Washington Redskins trash can.

00:02:07.210 --> 00:02:09.210
Now I've been going to
school in Washington.

00:02:09.210 --> 00:02:10.660
The Redskins were
good back then.

00:02:10.660 --> 00:02:12.680
So I said to the
guy off-handedly,

00:02:12.680 --> 00:02:15.140
that's an awesome trashcan.

00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:17.810
This hits the guy in
the emotional seat.

00:02:17.810 --> 00:02:20.730
And my 10 minute interview
becomes 15 minutes

00:02:20.730 --> 00:02:23.170
of him going on about
the virtues of athletics

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:26.390
and how much the football
team is a metaphor for life.

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:30.460
And I'm basically going
like this the whole time.

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:32.370
So I go back to school.

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:34.509
Couple weeks later I
get the coveted letter

00:02:34.509 --> 00:02:36.300
in the mail-- you've
been offered this job.

00:02:36.300 --> 00:02:37.009
This is great.

00:02:37.009 --> 00:02:38.800
I'm gainfully employed,
I move to New York,

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:41.030
and I start my job.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:44.091
About three months into
it, one of the senior guys

00:02:44.091 --> 00:02:46.340
in the program pulls me
aside, puts his arm around me,

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:47.970
says, hey, kid you're doing OK.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:48.910
Everything's fine.

00:02:48.910 --> 00:02:49.910
I just want you to know.

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:52.410
But I have to tell
you something now.

00:02:52.410 --> 00:02:56.790
The six people you interviewed
voted against hiring you.

00:02:56.790 --> 00:02:57.990
Very reassuring, right?

00:02:57.990 --> 00:02:59.850
So I'm like, OK,
so why am I here?

00:02:59.850 --> 00:03:01.390
And he said, well,
the senior guy

00:03:01.390 --> 00:03:03.870
came in and overrode
all their decisions.

00:03:03.870 --> 00:03:05.060
And he insisted we hire you.

00:03:05.060 --> 00:03:07.660
So I like to say my career
was launched by a trash can.

00:03:07.660 --> 00:03:09.750
And that was pure luck.

00:03:09.750 --> 00:03:11.975
And thankfully there are
no Laszlo Bock algorithms

00:03:11.975 --> 00:03:13.100
involved with that, either.

00:03:13.100 --> 00:03:15.494
Otherwise, I'd
still be unemployed.

00:03:15.494 --> 00:03:16.910
The topic today
is skill and luck.

00:03:16.910 --> 00:03:18.310
I really want to talk
about three things.

00:03:18.310 --> 00:03:19.960
First I want to
define my terms a bit

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:22.490
and talk about what I call
the three easy lessons-- three

00:03:22.490 --> 00:03:24.157
things you can take
away fairly quickly.

00:03:24.157 --> 00:03:26.198
In the middle part-- the
meat of the discussion--

00:03:26.198 --> 00:03:28.660
I want to talk about the
complexion of skill and luck--

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:30.950
what they look like and
how they change over time.

00:03:30.950 --> 00:03:33.780
And then finally I'll wrap up a
bit with what to do about this,

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:36.470
but also why we struggle
so much in our lives

00:03:36.470 --> 00:03:39.666
to understand the role of luck.

00:03:39.666 --> 00:03:41.290
One way to think
about this is to think

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:42.710
about a continuum of activities.

00:03:42.710 --> 00:03:45.090
On the far left--
pure luck, no skill.

00:03:45.090 --> 00:03:47.750
You might think lotteries
or roulette wheels.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:51.600
On the far right--
pure skill, no luck.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:55.180
Maybe running races or
chess would be over there.

00:03:55.180 --> 00:03:56.750
It's very important
to define terms.

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:58.190
So let me just take
a moment to do that.

00:03:58.190 --> 00:03:59.648
I'm going to define
skill right out

00:03:59.648 --> 00:04:01.570
of the dictionary,
which is the ability

00:04:01.570 --> 00:04:04.234
to apply one's knowledge readily
in execution or performance.

00:04:04.234 --> 00:04:05.900
So you know how to
do something and when

00:04:05.900 --> 00:04:09.006
you're called on to do
it, you can do it on cue.

00:04:09.006 --> 00:04:10.380
Now luck-- as you
might imagine--

00:04:10.380 --> 00:04:11.680
is much more
difficult to define.

00:04:11.680 --> 00:04:13.960
It actually spills into moral
philosophy quite quickly.

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:15.090
But I'm going to
say luck exists when

00:04:15.090 --> 00:04:16.310
three conditions are in place.

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:18.809
Number one is it operates for
an individual or organization.

00:04:18.809 --> 00:04:21.990
So it happens to you, or your
favorite team, or your company.

00:04:21.990 --> 00:04:23.747
The second is it
could be good or bad.

00:04:23.747 --> 00:04:25.580
And I don't mean to
suggest it's symmetrical

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:26.960
because we'll see in a few
moments it's certainly not

00:04:26.960 --> 00:04:27.460
symmetrical.

00:04:27.460 --> 00:04:30.520
But there's a plus sign
and a minus sign possible.

00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:32.700
And third is it is
reasonable to expect

00:04:32.700 --> 00:04:34.610
a different outcome
could have occurred.

00:04:34.610 --> 00:04:37.355
So if we rewound the tape of
time and we played it again,

00:04:37.355 --> 00:04:39.690
it's reasonable to expect
a different outcome could

00:04:39.690 --> 00:04:41.300
have occurred.

00:04:41.300 --> 00:04:45.130
Now what I've done here for fun
is arrayed professional sports

00:04:45.130 --> 00:04:48.997
leagues based on one
season of performance.

00:04:48.997 --> 00:04:50.413
So this is where
they actually lie

00:04:50.413 --> 00:04:51.579
on the luck/skill continuum.

00:04:51.579 --> 00:04:55.910
That's the NBA, Barclays Premier
League Soccer, Major League

00:04:55.910 --> 00:04:59.875
Baseball, the NFL, and
then finally the NHL.

00:04:59.875 --> 00:05:02.000
Now I'll mention one other
thing on luck and skill,

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:02.750
which is kind of fun.

00:05:02.750 --> 00:05:03.880
There's a really
interesting test

00:05:03.880 --> 00:05:05.509
which I learned from
the poker people

00:05:05.509 --> 00:05:07.800
about figuring out if there's
any skill in an activity.

00:05:07.800 --> 00:05:11.580
And that is, ask if you
can lose on purpose.

00:05:11.580 --> 00:05:14.010
If you can lose on purpose,
there must be some skill.

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:16.550
If you can't lose on purpose,
it's basically all luck.

00:05:16.550 --> 00:05:19.465
So that's another nice little
litmus test to figure that out.

00:05:22.190 --> 00:05:24.810
I'm going to go through this
very quickly, mostly as a set

00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:27.240
up for the next discussion.

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:29.730
You might imagine that
your outcome in life

00:05:29.730 --> 00:05:31.960
is drawing from a luck
distribution and a skill

00:05:31.960 --> 00:05:32.510
distribution.

00:05:32.510 --> 00:05:34.840
So I take the two
outcomes and combine them,

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:36.411
and that's going
to be my outcome.

00:05:36.411 --> 00:05:38.535
So in the far left it would
be a luck distribution,

00:05:38.535 --> 00:05:40.409
and you're drawing
only zeros for skill.

00:05:40.409 --> 00:05:42.200
So only luck is going
to make a difference.

00:05:42.200 --> 00:05:43.616
On the right it's
going be drawing

00:05:43.616 --> 00:05:45.830
from a skill distribution
and zeros from luck.

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:46.960
So only skill matters.

00:05:46.960 --> 00:05:48.460
And then everything
in life is going

00:05:48.460 --> 00:05:50.240
to be some
distribution for each.

00:05:50.240 --> 00:05:51.781
So we're drawing
these distributions.

00:05:51.781 --> 00:05:54.170
So this very simplistic
set up allows

00:05:54.170 --> 00:05:57.250
me to proceed with what I
call the three easy lessons.

00:05:57.250 --> 00:06:00.590
So easy lesson
number one-- whenever

00:06:00.590 --> 00:06:02.500
you see an extreme
outlier-- and by the way,

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:04.370
most of the outliers
we observe are positive

00:06:04.370 --> 00:06:07.260
outliers because negative
outliers almost always die,

00:06:07.260 --> 00:06:09.190
either literally
or metaphorically.

00:06:09.190 --> 00:06:10.820
So whenever you see
a positive outlier,

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:14.445
it's always the combination of
great skill plus great luck.

00:06:14.445 --> 00:06:16.070
And if you think
about it for a moment,

00:06:16.070 --> 00:06:17.530
that really has to be true.

00:06:17.530 --> 00:06:20.479
It's a right hand draw from
both of those distributions.

00:06:20.479 --> 00:06:22.520
Now there are many ways
I could demonstrate this.

00:06:22.520 --> 00:06:24.603
One of the convenient ways
is the world of sports.

00:06:24.603 --> 00:06:26.080
This, of course,
is Joe DiMaggio,

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:30.400
who hit in 56 straight
games in 1941.

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:33.740
DiMaggio was a
.325 career hitter,

00:06:33.740 --> 00:06:35.159
one of the best of all time.

00:06:35.159 --> 00:06:37.450
And it turns out if you look
at all the players with 30

00:06:37.450 --> 00:06:40.300
or more hitting streaks,
their career batting average

00:06:40.300 --> 00:06:41.220
is over .300.

00:06:41.220 --> 00:06:43.340
They're about one and a
half standard deviations

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:45.080
above the average.

00:06:45.080 --> 00:06:46.980
So saying this very
differently-- not

00:06:46.980 --> 00:06:50.510
all skillful players
have streaks,

00:06:50.510 --> 00:06:52.869
but all the streaks are
held by skillful players.

00:06:52.869 --> 00:06:53.910
And it make sense, right?

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:55.909
Because skill is the
prerequisite, and then luck

00:06:55.909 --> 00:06:59.120
comes on top to get
to be an outlier.

00:06:59.120 --> 00:07:00.870
The second observation--
second lesson--

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:02.430
is about reversion to the mean.

00:07:02.430 --> 00:07:03.240
By the way,
reversion to the mean

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:04.656
is a fascinating
concept because I

00:07:04.656 --> 00:07:07.247
think most people have a sense
that they know what it means.

00:07:07.247 --> 00:07:09.580
But if you actually observe
the behavior of most people,

00:07:09.580 --> 00:07:11.250
they don't act as if
they understand reversion

00:07:11.250 --> 00:07:11.530
to the mean.

00:07:11.530 --> 00:07:12.696
So let me just be technical.

00:07:12.696 --> 00:07:13.910
You guys all understand this.

00:07:13.910 --> 00:07:16.159
Reversion to the mean says
that an outcome that is far

00:07:16.159 --> 00:07:18.450
from average will be
followed by an outcome

00:07:18.450 --> 00:07:20.860
with an expected value
closer to the average.

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:21.360
Right?

00:07:21.360 --> 00:07:22.910
Now here's the
classic example, which

00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:24.743
you may remember from
your stats class years

00:07:24.743 --> 00:07:27.160
ago-- the heights
of fathers and sons.

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:28.974
Very tall fathers
have tall sons.

00:07:28.974 --> 00:07:31.140
But the heights of the sons
are close to the average

00:07:31.140 --> 00:07:32.260
of all the sons.

00:07:32.260 --> 00:07:34.094
And likewise, short
fathers have short sons.

00:07:34.094 --> 00:07:36.259
But the heights of the sons
are close to the average

00:07:36.259 --> 00:07:37.462
of all heights of the sons.

00:07:37.462 --> 00:07:38.920
Now here's the one
thing I think is

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:41.130
very interesting
and practical about

00:07:41.130 --> 00:07:43.410
this reversion to the mean
concept and the skill/luck

00:07:43.410 --> 00:07:46.120
continuum, which is it
turns out where you lie

00:07:46.120 --> 00:07:49.170
on the luck/skill continuum
defines the rate of reversion

00:07:49.170 --> 00:07:51.110
to the mean-- not
just that it occurs,

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:52.990
but the rate of
reversion to the mean.

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:54.930
So for example, if
you're on the pure luck

00:07:54.930 --> 00:07:57.657
side of the continuum, there's
complete reversion to the mean.

00:07:57.657 --> 00:07:59.740
In other words, expected
value of the next outcome

00:07:59.740 --> 00:08:02.450
is some measure of the
average, mean, or in some cases

00:08:02.450 --> 00:08:03.900
the mode.

00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.490
If you're on the pure skill
side of the continuum,

00:08:06.490 --> 00:08:08.330
there's no reversion
to the mean at all.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:11.130
We run a sprint against
Usain Bolt, he wins.

00:08:11.130 --> 00:08:13.360
We run again, he wins again.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:14.920
No reversion to the mean.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:17.200
So if you know where
your activity is,

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:19.865
you automatically have a sense
for the rate of reversion

00:08:19.865 --> 00:08:20.365
to the mean.

00:08:20.365 --> 00:08:22.364
So if you're thinking
about things like business

00:08:22.364 --> 00:08:24.040
performance or markets
or what have you,

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:28.172
it's a very, very helpful
and useful heuristic.

00:08:28.172 --> 00:08:30.130
Now the third lesson is
the one that's probably

00:08:30.130 --> 00:08:32.840
garnered the most
interest from this book.

00:08:32.840 --> 00:08:34.872
It's a concept I call
the paradox of skill.

00:08:34.872 --> 00:08:36.580
I want to be clear
that it's not my idea,

00:08:36.580 --> 00:08:38.008
but I gave it that name.

00:08:38.008 --> 00:08:40.549
And the paradox of skills says
in activities where both skill

00:08:40.549 --> 00:08:43.890
and luck contribute to
outcomes, it is often the case

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:47.060
that as skill increases--
skill improves--

00:08:47.060 --> 00:08:49.580
luck becomes more important.

00:08:49.580 --> 00:08:51.450
So how can we have
more skill leading

00:08:51.450 --> 00:08:53.330
to more luck being important?

00:08:53.330 --> 00:08:55.930
Now I learned about this
concept from Stephen Jay Gould,

00:08:55.930 --> 00:08:57.934
a very eminent
biologist who wrote

00:08:57.934 --> 00:08:59.850
a lot about evolutionary
theory and also liked

00:08:59.850 --> 00:09:01.580
to write about baseball.

00:09:01.580 --> 00:09:03.200
And one of my favorite
essays he wrote

00:09:03.200 --> 00:09:05.650
was about Ted Williams,
who you see here.

00:09:05.650 --> 00:09:07.640
Ted Williams was the
last player to hit over

00:09:07.640 --> 00:09:11.020
.400 in Major League Baseball.

00:09:11.020 --> 00:09:12.730
He also did it in the year 1941.

00:09:12.730 --> 00:09:14.590
And so the question
Gould was pondering

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:16.480
is why has no one
been able to replicate

00:09:16.480 --> 00:09:19.652
this feat over the
ensuing 70 plus years?

00:09:19.652 --> 00:09:22.110
He said maybe it's because the
players play at night, maybe

00:09:22.110 --> 00:09:23.693
because there are
relief pitchers now,

00:09:23.693 --> 00:09:26.870
maybe-- none of these
things actually checked out.

00:09:26.870 --> 00:09:30.030
The answer was, it turns out
the standard deviation of skill

00:09:30.030 --> 00:09:32.420
for Major League Baseball
players has gotten narrower,

00:09:32.420 --> 00:09:35.460
which is to say the difference
between the very best players

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:37.860
and the average
players is less today

00:09:37.860 --> 00:09:40.130
than it was a generation ago.

00:09:40.130 --> 00:09:41.820
So if you accept that
batting average is

00:09:41.820 --> 00:09:44.570
some skill plus
some luck combined,

00:09:44.570 --> 00:09:48.554
if the standard deviation
of skill goes down,

00:09:48.554 --> 00:09:50.720
that means the standard
deviation of batting average

00:09:50.720 --> 00:09:51.010
should go down.

00:09:51.010 --> 00:09:53.260
And that's, indeed,
precisely what we've seen.

00:09:53.260 --> 00:09:55.750
So the standard deviation of
batting average in the 1940s

00:09:55.750 --> 00:09:57.386
was .032.

00:09:57.386 --> 00:09:59.510
And the standard deviation
of batting average today

00:09:59.510 --> 00:10:01.220
is about .027.

00:10:01.220 --> 00:10:03.010
So saying this
differently, Ted Williams

00:10:03.010 --> 00:10:06.710
was a four standard
deviation event in 1941.

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:10.167
And if you were a four standard
deviation event in 2011--

00:10:10.167 --> 00:10:12.083
let's say 70 years later--
you would hit .380.

00:10:12.083 --> 00:10:14.500
Now .380 is obviously fantastic.

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:17.642
But it doesn't get you over
that threshold of .400.

00:10:17.642 --> 00:10:19.350
Now here's the thing
I want to emphasize.

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:22.490
It turns out the paradox of
skill is everywhere we look.

00:10:22.490 --> 00:10:24.160
It's very visibly
true in the world

00:10:24.160 --> 00:10:26.990
of investing where the standard
deviation of excess returns

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:29.685
has been coming down
steadily for 50 years.

00:10:29.685 --> 00:10:31.060
It's true in the
world of sports,

00:10:31.060 --> 00:10:32.322
as I've already mentioned.

00:10:32.322 --> 00:10:34.030
It's also true in the
world of business--

00:10:34.030 --> 00:10:35.640
for example,
quality of products.

00:10:35.640 --> 00:10:38.290
Now it's much more uniform
than it was a generation or two

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:39.820
before.

00:10:39.820 --> 00:10:41.994
I want to leave you
with this one thought.

00:10:41.994 --> 00:10:43.410
The distinction
I'm making here is

00:10:43.410 --> 00:10:45.872
that absolute skill
has never been higher.

00:10:45.872 --> 00:10:47.330
And that's true
everywhere we look.

00:10:47.330 --> 00:10:50.420
But relative skill has
never been narrower.

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:52.060
That means more is
being left to luck.

00:10:52.060 --> 00:10:53.810
And I want to just
keep that in your mind.

00:10:53.810 --> 00:10:56.030
More is being left to
luck in our modern world

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:57.460
than it has been in years past.

00:10:57.460 --> 00:10:59.230
We'll come back to
that in a few moments.

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:00.730
So those are the
three easy lessons.

00:11:00.730 --> 00:11:03.580
The paradox skill says as
absolute skill improves,

00:11:03.580 --> 00:11:05.069
if relative skill
comes down, more

00:11:05.069 --> 00:11:06.610
is actually going
to be left to luck.

00:11:09.995 --> 00:11:12.120
The paradox of skill actually
makes a very specific

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:13.470
prediction which
is, in realms where

00:11:13.470 --> 00:11:15.750
there is no luck we should
see two things happening--

00:11:15.750 --> 00:11:17.420
if my description is correct.

00:11:17.420 --> 00:11:19.895
One is an absolute improvement--
in this case grinding

00:11:19.895 --> 00:11:21.880
to some physiological limit.

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:23.770
I'm using an athletic
endeavor here.

00:11:23.770 --> 00:11:25.630
And the second is
clustering because I'm

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:27.260
suggesting the right
tail is coming in.

00:11:27.260 --> 00:11:29.765
That means the performance is
getting clustered of people.

00:11:29.765 --> 00:11:31.140
So there are many
ways I can show

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:32.400
this is actually occurring.

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:35.830
One convenient example is
Olympic men's marathon time.

00:11:35.830 --> 00:11:37.940
So the white line
there is the time

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:39.500
of the guy who won
the gold medal.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:42.570
And you can see that
guy ran-- in 2012--

00:11:42.570 --> 00:11:45.625
about 23 and a half minutes
faster than the guy who

00:11:45.625 --> 00:11:47.790
won the gold medal in 1932.

00:11:47.790 --> 00:11:49.230
So not a huge surprise.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:52.160
But if you're a runner, it's
about a minute a mile pace

00:11:52.160 --> 00:11:54.280
pick up over 80 years.

00:11:54.280 --> 00:11:56.030
The more interesting
line is the blue one,

00:11:56.030 --> 00:11:57.821
which is the difference
between the guy who

00:11:57.821 --> 00:11:59.977
won the gold medal and
the guy who came in 20th.

00:11:59.977 --> 00:12:02.560
Now mind you, this is supposed
to be some of the best, fastest

00:12:02.560 --> 00:12:06.170
runners in the world
competing on the same stage.

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:10.660
That difference was
39 minutes in 1932.

00:12:10.660 --> 00:12:12.190
Now just take that
in for a second.

00:12:12.190 --> 00:12:14.570
This is the Olympic marathon.

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:17.694
The guy has won the gold
medal, has taken a shower,

00:12:17.694 --> 00:12:19.360
is eating a sandwich,
and this other guy

00:12:19.360 --> 00:12:23.590
is still on the
course finishing up.

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:26.134
That time is down to about five
minutes, seven minutes today.

00:12:26.134 --> 00:12:27.550
And I think we can
confidently say

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:29.810
if we meet in the
future, that will

00:12:29.810 --> 00:12:32.260
be an even shorter
amount of time.

00:12:32.260 --> 00:12:36.770
So we see in swimming,
rowing, running,

00:12:36.770 --> 00:12:38.530
this convergence of times.

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:41.300
And as you know, we need now
incredibly sensitive devices

00:12:41.300 --> 00:12:43.170
just to figure out
when the players leave

00:12:43.170 --> 00:12:45.490
and when they finish in
order to measure truly

00:12:45.490 --> 00:12:50.550
which one is the fastest
in that particular event.

00:12:50.550 --> 00:12:53.515
Let me shift gears a bit and
now talk about skill/luck.

00:12:53.515 --> 00:12:55.890
I've been depicting them with
these normal distributions,

00:12:55.890 --> 00:12:57.819
but of course,
that's not the case.

00:12:57.819 --> 00:12:59.110
Skill-- let me start with that.

00:12:59.110 --> 00:13:01.010
It's actually quite
easy to describe.

00:13:01.010 --> 00:13:02.930
Skill tends to follow an arc.

00:13:02.930 --> 00:13:05.254
So we call this
the arc of skill.

00:13:05.254 --> 00:13:07.170
Again, let me start with
a physical endeavour.

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:08.355
This is sports.

00:13:08.355 --> 00:13:10.230
So for example, if you've
ever played a sport

00:13:10.230 --> 00:13:11.771
when you start off
when you're young,

00:13:11.771 --> 00:13:13.450
you don't have a
lot of proficiency.

00:13:13.450 --> 00:13:15.950
But as you practice, you get
better, and better, and better.

00:13:15.950 --> 00:13:18.566
At some point you get
to peak performance

00:13:18.566 --> 00:13:19.690
as you're getting stronger.

00:13:19.690 --> 00:13:21.273
And then you come
down the other side.

00:13:21.273 --> 00:13:22.980
So there's this
very definable arc.

00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:25.160
By the way, for sports the
best way to predict this

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:27.760
is slow twitch versus
fast twitch muscles.

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:31.090
It turns out that in sports with
a lot of fast twitch muscles,

00:13:31.090 --> 00:13:32.160
players peak young.

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:34.480
So sprinters-- 22, 23.

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:36.640
Basketball players--
their mid-20s.

00:13:36.640 --> 00:13:38.450
And then if there's
more slow twitch,

00:13:38.450 --> 00:13:40.660
you peak in your
late 20s, typically.

00:13:40.660 --> 00:13:43.720
So baseball players-- late 20s.

00:13:43.720 --> 00:13:46.095
Some football players--
late 20s, as well.

00:13:46.095 --> 00:13:48.720
By the way, if you're a golfer,
there's some good news for you.

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:51.770
Golf tends to plateau
from roughly 30 to 35,

00:13:51.770 --> 00:13:54.625
and then it rolls
over after age 35.

00:13:54.625 --> 00:13:57.172
So here's Tiger
Woods, who is now 38.

00:13:57.172 --> 00:13:59.380
So no matter what other
issues he's dealing with now,

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:03.410
Father Time is also
knocking on his door.

00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:05.800
Here's the actual arc
of skill for tennis.

00:14:05.800 --> 00:14:07.380
This is quite interesting data.

00:14:07.380 --> 00:14:11.980
This is the winner of Men's
Grand Slam tournaments

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:12.750
in the Open era.

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:15.450
So 1968 through 2013.

00:14:15.450 --> 00:14:17.840
So on top you can
see the distribution.

00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:21.180
And it turns out, the
mode is 24 years old.

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:22.850
And it turns out in
the last 40 years

00:14:22.850 --> 00:14:25.280
or so, the mean is
actually 24 years old.

00:14:25.280 --> 00:14:28.280
So 24 years old is
basically the sweet spot

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:30.402
for winning men's
tennis tournaments.

00:14:30.402 --> 00:14:32.110
Now the bottom panel--
it's a little hard

00:14:32.110 --> 00:14:33.430
to see from where you
are-- but the bottom

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:35.990
is actually the age of every
winner of every tournament

00:14:35.990 --> 00:14:39.870
since that time, with
a line at age 30.

00:14:39.870 --> 00:14:46.580
And what we know is in the
last 40 years-- so 160 events--

00:14:46.580 --> 00:14:49.880
only four players have
been over 30 years

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:52.190
old who've won a Grand Slam.

00:14:52.190 --> 00:14:53.140
Only four players.

00:14:53.140 --> 00:14:55.092
By the way, we had a
little bit of excitement

00:14:55.092 --> 00:14:57.300
about this just a couple
weeks ago with Roger Federer

00:14:57.300 --> 00:14:58.370
trying to win Wimbledon.

00:14:58.370 --> 00:14:59.720
He's 32 years old.

00:14:59.720 --> 00:15:02.330
He'll be 33 in the fall.

00:15:02.330 --> 00:15:06.470
It's simply no one has won
Wimbledon over the age of 30

00:15:06.470 --> 00:15:08.940
since Arthur Ash did it in 1975.

00:15:08.940 --> 00:15:12.490
So it was really-- it just shows
you how amazing Federer is.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:15.570
But at his age, with
17 Slams, what happens

00:15:15.570 --> 00:15:18.149
is you physically slow
down just a tiny bit.

00:15:18.149 --> 00:15:19.690
And that difference
is the difference

00:15:19.690 --> 00:15:21.360
between you and a
younger generation.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.050
So we'll see if in men's tennis
this new, young generation

00:15:24.050 --> 00:15:26.380
starts to take over.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:28.460
This is a very, very
pronounced pattern

00:15:28.460 --> 00:15:34.120
that we see in every sport
and you know, bankable.

00:15:34.120 --> 00:15:36.699
Now your reaction to that is
probably something like, oh,

00:15:36.699 --> 00:15:37.490
that's interesting.

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:39.370
Maybe it helps you in your
fantasy sports league,

00:15:39.370 --> 00:15:39.911
or something.

00:15:39.911 --> 00:15:42.600
But what you care about is
cognitive performance, right?

00:15:42.600 --> 00:15:44.350
Psychologists study
cognitive performance.

00:15:44.350 --> 00:15:46.300
And it follows the
same arc, incidentally.

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:48.720
And it turns out
psychologists often

00:15:48.720 --> 00:15:50.270
agree that cognitive
performance is

00:15:50.270 --> 00:15:52.050
a function of two
types of intelligence--

00:15:52.050 --> 00:15:54.759
so-called crystallized
and fluid intelligence.

00:15:54.759 --> 00:15:56.300
And you can see from
the picture this

00:15:56.300 --> 00:15:59.339
is sort of a bad news,
good news situation.

00:15:59.339 --> 00:16:01.880
Let's start with the bad news,
and that's fluid intelligence.

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:03.300
So fluid intelligence
is effectively

00:16:03.300 --> 00:16:04.740
your ability to
deal with novelty.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:06.470
So if I present you with
a series you've never

00:16:06.470 --> 00:16:08.470
seen before, how good
are you at figuring out

00:16:08.470 --> 00:16:10.760
what's going to happen next?

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:12.280
Turns out we have
a couple people

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:14.840
who are probably right at
their peaks in the room.

00:16:14.840 --> 00:16:16.997
Fluid intelligence tends
to peak in your early 20s

00:16:16.997 --> 00:16:19.330
and then pretty much goes
downhill throughout your life.

00:16:19.330 --> 00:16:22.182
So if you're out of
college, basically, you're

00:16:22.182 --> 00:16:23.640
probably on the
down swing in terms

00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:25.185
of your fluid intelligence.

00:16:25.185 --> 00:16:26.560
Crystallized
intelligence-- which

00:16:26.560 --> 00:16:29.150
is the good news, of
course-- is something

00:16:29.150 --> 00:16:30.680
that is exactly
what it sounds like.

00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:31.680
It's your cumulative knowledge.

00:16:31.680 --> 00:16:33.960
It's your wisdom, understanding
of facts, and so forth.

00:16:33.960 --> 00:16:35.920
That pretty much-- barring
cognitive impairment--

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:37.350
pretty much grows
throughout life.

00:16:37.350 --> 00:16:38.290
So you can see that.

00:16:38.290 --> 00:16:41.700
And it's the combination that
defines this overall arc.

00:16:41.700 --> 00:16:43.514
So here are the
basic trade offs.

00:16:43.514 --> 00:16:45.430
Now I just want to
mentioned a couple numbers,

00:16:45.430 --> 00:16:47.221
